nodes.title: Important
widgets_values:
If you want to keep the same style throughout multiple batches, you need to use the same reference photo. It's not perfect but sometimes works well

If you generated with your own photo you don't need to change anything, if you generated one, you need to save the image and load it in the loader above.  Then connect the loader to the ref used. This will use the same reference each batch
right click and set group nodes to never to hold the previews here until you get the preview to the right correct with the options

Crop the input control nets

Useful to reposition the subject in the frame

Right click and bypass group nodes to disable

Can upscale your controlnets here

This determines your generation size
MP4 needs specific sizes, if error change scale by .01
Same issue with masks sometimes its too small.

This is creating an image for IP adaptor to try to match, trying to hold the image for the full clip

It's using open pose or HED to do a pose similar to what your video has, and imports the background mostly from a tile from the previous step

It offers you the ability to see how well your model does with the control nets and how they fit the background, it's easier to cut feet out

If you prefer, you can bypass this group and just upload a reference image you already have.  Just connect the load image node to the Used ref node and bypass this group

Loading the control nets

As long as you made the control nets in the previous step or are using the examples, you can load in the control nets here by choosing the Video name

Options are

Load every, lets you skip frames, lowers fps
I rarely use this to go below 12fps, I prefer to make them in 12fps in the preprocessor workflow

Starting frame lets you start at whatever frame you want from the control net files.

Max frames are how many frames you are bringing in.

You can crop and upscale/downscale here and outpaint pad.

Ip adaptor is great for keeping consistency but not perfect.

Animate diff settings for 32 frames are 16-2-0.  You dont really need overlap when you are directing the motion with controlnets.  
48 frames can work, if you have the memory for it.  I think its 16-4-0 for settings.

Finally the video.... 

This uses LCM Lora at 12 steps sgm uniform to get a consistent video.  6-14 steps is recommended.  This depends highly on your model and how well it uses animate diff and lcm.. Some don't like it, some take 6 steps for decent results. I don't recommend below 12 due to inconsistency and distortions, but it can work. CFG 1.3-2.2

Methods used to get consistency 

This uses ipadaptor plus to hold a consistent character though out a video, still not perfect, but it's getting close, can mask off the subject in ipadaptor to just affect the person if you want
Can use a line art/tile mix to hold the background to something stable. or just use pix2pix
Can use open pose/depth to hold the subject animation intact
Uses animate diff scrolling context to get fluid frames
Masks off both background and subject to try not to blend the two together.

Control net strengths.

Open pose can be 0.5-1 depending on how good your images are, you can use 1 with good images, but if there are some anomalies lessen the strength
Depth can 0.6-0.9 depending on how strong your open pose is, with a strong open pose you can use less here, with a weak one a strong depth can help.  The stronger it is, the less it can change clothing and fights ip adaptor (if morphing clothing is a problem, lower this weight

Lineart and HED both can be used to copy the video quite well with .7-.9 with the depth map.  Or can do it alone and see results. 

Line+tile background
Lineart background should be 1 for static, and 0.8-0.9 for slight animated background, like grass sway, trees in wind etc.
Tile background should be .5-.8 depending on how the colouring is.  Without it, line art does not get the depth of realism

pix2pix works better for background

Remember this is running through animate diff, so the strengths can give room for it to animate, especially when your control nets have flaws.

2 model options here.  not really needed anymore since i moved the upscale to another flow but options are there.

1 is used for animate diff and one can be used for everything else.  This can be the same model or a different one.  

The Used group has a model node and a Dmodel node.  Dmodel is used for animate diff only.  Model is used for everything else, I use this to use a more cartoon/anime style model with animate diff that tend to animate better and a more realistic model for the upscale and enhancements.

Loading of lcm loras here, any others can also be added. I use lcm loras at 0.6 strength to allow a higher cfg and to allow the original model to show through more.

Can load your own loras here to effect the output.

Clip skip should be set to your models advice.

nodes.title: Background Positive Prompt
widgets_values: dark hellish cave interior, empty, succubi lair, fire

This pre-processing could be done in this workflow, but even my 12gb 3060 threw fits and ran out of memory.  Separating preprocessing from the generation was the only real option and actually works much smoother.

Loading control nets - Note use .gif for previews.  .webp bugs out and loads wrong stuff sometimes.  Mp4 works but these are previews and you dont need to.  

All files should be in ComfyUI\output\myvideos\ in separate folders. 

These are created with the preprocess workflow from a video. Variety of different combos work, opose+depth is best if quality input.

Depth - used with openpose to ensure body motion depth stability
Opose - used to set the animation poses frame by frame
masks - used to apply the control nets to only effect the areas needed
lineart - used to replace opose when opose is bad or you dont need to change clothing/hairstyles
HED - Like lineart but can style it much better.

Control nets Yes ... im aware how crazy this setup looks.  Its mostly to cover all uses.  Not all should be used at once

Bypass the control nets you are not using.


Background
Depth can help with some animations .5 is usually good
pix2pix is the best IMO.  It copies the background colours and enhances them properly and gives a sharper background
Tile works second best, it keeps the stability, but loses colour. 
others can be combo with it or used solo. for slight background animations .8-.9 works. Grass sway, branch sway, fire.


Many combos work.  But not all combos work for every video. Sometimes just one works fine.

Opose + Depth
HED + depth
Line + depth
opose + HED
